[sub_resource type="Resource" id="Resource_00vgw"]
script = ExtResource("1_00vgw")
title = "ACT No. 199 — Forensic Examination
Written April 16, 1959.
In connection with the criminal case concerning the death of the tourist group led by Dyatlov, a camping tent recovered from the slope of height '1079' was submitted on April 3, 1959 by order of the Prosecutor’s Office of Sverdlovsk Region (reference 16/III-59) for forensic examination. The object of study consisted of a cotton expeditionary tent found at the presumed campsite from which the group departed under circumstances not yet fully established. The examination was assigned to expert-criminalist Churkina H.E., specialist in material trace analysis. The expert was formally warned of criminal liability under Articles 92 and 95 of the RSFSR Criminal Code. The principal questions posed were as follows: (1) whether the tent fabric had been deliberately incised or otherwise mechanically compromised; (2) if so, whether such compromise occurred by action originating within the enclosed interior space or by force applied externally."
paragraphs = Array[String](["Circumstances Noted in the Case File: investigative notes accompanying the tent mention that several bodies were later recovered with irregular or incomplete clothing layers, including reports consistent with paradoxical undressing. Medical literature describes this phenomenon sometimes observed in advanced hypothermia wherein affected individuals experience a sudden and irrational sensation of overheating. This state may produce confusion, impaired judgment, and a compulsion to remove insulating layers even while core body temperature continues to fall.", "Separate informal memoranda also reference the possibility of exposure to chemical or pharmacological substances capable of inducing agitation, hallucination, or erratic behavior. Mentions of compounds classified broadly as psychoactive agents, including substances such as LSD, appear in secondary commentary; however, no toxicological or contamination test confirmation is contained within this textile examination record.", "Condition of the Object Presented: the tent was received in a crumpled and partially collapsed state, bearing multiple deformations consistent with transport and environmental exposure. In order to approximate the original spatial configuration, the tent was reconstructed and erected with assistance from a professional hiker, who provided guidance regarding customary pitching method. Following reassembly, the textile structure was measured and documented. To determine directionality of action, microscopic examination was conducted at magnifications ranging from 0.6× to 56×. Alternative explanations sometimes proposed in non-technical commentary; animal damage or ice crystal tearing were considered only insofar as they might leave comparable micro-traces.", "From the left end of the tent there is a hole that serves as an entrance. When inspecting the tent, it is established that on its surface there are numerous damages, especially on the right slant of the canopy forming the roof. With a careful examination of these damages, it is established that some of them have a completely different nature compared to all the other damages that are on the tent. The edges of these three lesions have even, not elongated ends of the threads, are damaged at different angles, breaking both the weft threads and the warp threads. As a result of the foregoing, and when examining the edges of all the damages on the tent, one can conclude that three damages  came as a result of contact with some sharp weapon, i.e. the tent was cut open.", "In order to determine from which side the indicated cuts were made (from the inner one - from the tent or from the outside), a thorough microscopic examination of the edges of the cuts of the adjacent tissue sections was made. The nature and shape of all these injuries indicate that they were formed from the contact of the fabric of the inner side of the tent with the blade of some weapon knife. All of the above indicates that the existing incisions are made from the inside, from the tent.", "Items Recovered in Proximity to the Tent: numerous items found in the vicinity of the tent and surrounding slope could not be attributed to a confirmed owner. These included torn boot covers (nine pairs), cotton and wool socks in various states of wear, gloves, mittens balaclavas, repair materials, and spectacle frames. Among items recovered closest to the tent entrance were scraps of unidentified cloth and glasses fragments, the origin of which remained unestablished at the time of primary inspection.", "Two unassigned items of particular note were recovered from inside the tent’s inner pocket lining and referred immediately to attending officials: a bound field record designated the expedition logbook, and a sealed identification wallet containing what appeared to be KGB credentials issued under two separate names. Before Yuri Yudin could be asked to comment on either item during the subsequent scene inspection, both were removed from the table by officials. A third document, partially legible and bearing the heading Operation Markov, was similarly withheld. Yuri Yudin stated separately on the record that he had observed United States Military officials in Ivdel wearing items of similar marking. This account was not followed up within the scope of this examination."])
reveals_words = [Array[String](["paradoxical undressing"]), Array[String](["psychoactive agents"]), Array[String](["animal damage", "ice crystal tearing"]), Array[String](["cut open"]), Array[String](["knife", "from the inside"]), Array[String]([]), Array[String](["expedition logbook", "KGB credentials", "Yuri Yudin", "Operation Markov", "Yuri Yudin", "United States Military"])]

[sub_resource type="Resource" id="Resource_g8dr7"]
script = ExtResource("1_00vgw")
title = "Consolidated Autopsy Files
Autopsy Report — Georgiy Alekseevich Krivonischenko Act No. 3. Examination conducted March 4, 1959. Body recovered in proximity to forest edge. Decedent aged twenty-three. The body under examination is a male body of regular constitution and satisfactory nutrition. The head is turned slightly to the left. The right arm is bent upward at the elbow and the fingers are drawn inward toward the head. The left arm is flexed at the elbow and rests across the torso. The right leg is extended, while the left leg is bent at the hip and slightly at the knee. The deceased was clothed in partial garments at the time of recovery. The majority of insulating outer layers were absent. Despite winter conditions, the body was effectively only in underwear bearing the team code 5П1513. The absence of protective clothing in these conditions is notable. Upon reflection of the scalp, diffuse hemorrhage is noted in the right temporal region. The bones of the head and skull are intact although the same cannot be said of the hiker’s colleague."
paragraphs = Array[String](["Conclusion: Based on the examination of the body of Krivonischenko Georgiy Alekseevich, aged 23, and taking into account the circumstances of the case, death occurred as a result of low temperature exposure (freezing), as evidenced by organ congestion, petechial hemorrhages of the gastric mucosa, and severe frost injury of the extremities. The burn of the left lower limb is consistent with exposure to open flame and appears localized. External injuries in the form of abrasions and grazes may have resulted from falls or contact with stones, ice, or other hard surfaces. These injuries were sustained during life, in the agonal state, or post mortem. No alcohol was detected. The skin in the region of the forehead and brow showed absence of hair and tissue, including the loss of the eyebrows. The eyes were partially degraded. No massive skeletal fractures were detected upon preliminary palpation. The chest cavity did not demonstrate the same degree of structural instability as seen in Dubinina or Zolotaryov.", "Autopsy Report — Igor Alekseevich Dyatlov Act No. 1. Examination conducted March 4, 1959, at the Regional Bureau of Forensic Medicine. The body of Dyatlov Igor Alekseevich, age twenty‑three, was presented for post‑mortem examination following recovery from mountainous terrain under winter conditions. The deceased was the registered leader of a hiking group whose members perished under undetermined circumstances. This report is to be read in conjunction with Acts No. 2 through 6. Examining pathologist notes that findings for Igor Dyatlov diverge in several significant aspects from the other recovered bodies.", "External inspection revealed a young adult male of athletic build. The body was recovered in a partially upright posture, upper extremities extended forward, consistent with attempted locomotion at time of death. The deceased was fully clothed in multiple insulating layers appropriate to the conditions, unlike several others in the group. Body was received wearing a padded outer jacket, ski pants, woollen underlayers, and a secret, sealed inner chest pocket.", "The skin of Dyatlov’s face is a blue-red color. Postmortem lividity is present with blue-red spots abundantly located on the posterior surface of the neck, torso and extremities. Rigor mortis has resolved in the muscle groups of the joints. The skin of the upper limbs down to the wrist joints are of bluish-pink color. Notably, circumferential bruising is present around the neck in a pattern distinct from any bruising observed on other recovered bodies. The contusion band measures approximately 3 cm in width and exhibits uniform pressure distribution consistent with choking. No equivalent injury pattern was identified on any other member of the group.", "Conclusion: based on the data of the examination of the body of Dyatlov Igor Alekseevich, 23 years old, and considering the circumstances of the case, the injuries documented in this report are not consistent with environmental exposure alone. The circumferential bruising of the neck and internal laryngeal hemorrhaging indicate that the deceased was attacked and choked to death. Freezing subsequently accelerated death. The presence of an unidentified compound in tissue samples and the classified secondary identification document found on the body were referred to a separate authority. This report was filed without a formal finding of homicide. The examining pathologist notes this omission under protest.", "Autopsy Report — Yuri Nikolaevich Doroshenko: Act No. 2. Examination conducted March 4, 1959. Body of Doroshenko Yuri Nikolaevich, age twenty‑one, recovered from a forested area near the expedition campsite. The body under examination is a male body of regular build. The body position is as follows: the upper limbs are drawn up at the shoulder joints towards the head and are bent at the elbow joints. The finger joints are also bent. The lower limbs are stretched. The head is turned to the left. The deceased was clothed in partial garments at the time of recovery, though examination of layering revealed the conspicuous absence of outer insulating articles. Despite prevailing sub-zero conditions, the body was effectively only in underwear with minimal additional textile coverage, limited to thin underlayers and damaged hosiery. On the inside of the pants, there is an identification tag reading 5П1513.", "Combined Autopsy Report - Ravine recovery Examination conducted May 9–10, 1959. Bodies recovered May 4, 1959 from a ravine approximately 75 meters from the cedar tree, beneath a snow layer measuring up to two meters in depth. The bodies were located in a running stream bed. The deceased were identified as: Lyudmila Aleksandrovna Dubinina, age 20, Semyon (Alexander) Zolotaryov, age 38, Alexander Kolevatov, age 24, Nikolai Thibeaux-Brignolles, age 23. The bodies were found in proximity to one another in the ravine channel, partially submerged in flowing water. General Observations: All four bodies were dressed in multiple layers of clothing at the time of recovery. It was established during inspection that several garments did not correspond to the original owners, and certain articles previously documented on other deceased members were now present on these bodies. The clothing therefore included items belonging to other members of the group; effectively the clothes of the previous bodies.", "Several garments were removed for laboratory testing. Subsequent analysis revealed measurable contamination of some clothing items with elevated levels of beta radiation. The degree of contamination varied between samples and was not uniformly distributed. For the purposes of record, the garments were described as radioactive. All four bodies displayed post-mortem changes consistent with prolonged exposure to water and burial beneath snow."])
reveals_words = [Array[String](["Krivonischenko", "eyebrows"]), Array[String]([]), Array[String](["ski pants"]), Array[String](["neck", "torso", "wrist", "neck"]), Array[String](["neck", "compound"]), Array[String](["elbow"]), Array[String](["Dubinina", "Thibeaux-Brignolles", "the clothes of the previous bodies"]), Array[String](["radiation", "radioactive"])]

[sub_resource type="Resource" id="Resource_gr0m5"]
script = ExtResource("1_00vgw")
title = "Case File 12 — Ownership of Items Recovered at Scene
Ivdel. 5–7 March 1959.
Junior Counselor of Justice Ivanov, acting in accordance with Article 78 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, conducted a formal inspection of material evidence recovered from the vicinity of the tent site of the deceased tourist group, as well as from the forested area containing traces of a fire and the bodies later identified as Krivonischenko and Doroshenko. The inspection was carried out in the presence of representatives of the Ural Polytechnic Institute and members of the press. Among those present for purposes of identification was fourth-year student of UPI, Yuri Yudin, who had separated from the expedition earlier due to illness and was the survivor therefore considered capable of recognizing group property based on personal familiarity, diary entries, and shared preparation of equipment."
paragraphs = Array[String](["The tent and surrounding equipment were found partially collapsed and covered with windblown snow. The tent was cut open from the inside. However, no conclusive evidence of structural compression by avalanche mass, snow slab, or snow drift displacement was recorded at the time of inspection, although snow accumulation patterns were noted. All materials collected were tested for contamination of various kinds. Results of contamination tests are presented in a separate autopsy report.", "1. A black backpack of worn construction  with a repaired side seam contained personal hygiene items, letters addressed to Kolmogorova, medical supplies including bandages and iodine, powdered milk tins, and a flashlight was assigned to Yuri Yudin]. According to Yuri, certain medical articles within the pack had been transferred to Kolmogorova at the Second Northern settlement when he departed the group. Garments included quilted outerwear, multiple pairs of woolen and vigogne socks, mended tent material and globes. When asked to confirm the route he had taken after departing the group, Yuri Yudin stated he had [[doubled back only as far as the Second Northern settlement to pass the medical equipment to Kolmogorova before continuing toward Vizhai by sled. No independent corroboration of this account was sought at this stage of proceedings.", "2. Property Attributed to Igor Dyatlov Recovered articles included a fur vest, tarpaulin outer garments, woolen hat, coarse mittens, and ski equipment. Within the pockets were located a notebook, compass, pocketknife secured by cord, rope segments, and personal eyewear in a grey case. Of interest, a hidden pocket within Igor’s pack contained KGB credentials and a small gas mask. Yuri stated on the record that he was unaware of Igor’s relation to the intelligence organisation. A fur vest discovered on Dyatlov’s body was stated by Yuri Yudin to have originally belonged to him and to have been given to Igor on 28 January 1959, suggesting subsequent exchange among participants. Such exchanges complicate strict attribution of items. Additional red-stained fabric, a torn strap, and a broken frame possibly belonging to eyewear were documented but not conclusively linked to a particular owner. Results of contamination tests are presented in a separate autopsy report.", "3. Property Attributed to Lyudmila Dubinina: a black backpack containing toiletries, broken spectacles, letters, elastic bandage, writing instruments, and a hiking badge pinned above the pocket was identified as Dubinina’s. Clothing layers included ski trousers, balaclava, felt boots, and multiple sock types. Yuri Yudin stated he had personally given her grey wool socks prior to his departure. The repetition of redistributed garments among members requires consideration in any analysis of final clothing configuration. Items located near the ravine area included additional torn textile, fragments of insulation, and distorted metal fittings. These materials were not immediately identifiable as belonging to any one member.", "4. Property Attributed to Rustem Slobodin: a khaki backpack marked with a small rubber toy bear contained binoculars, camera equipment, repair tools, notebooks, and sewing materials. On the body were discovered multiple clothing layers including sweater, checkered shirt, insoles placed between garments, and four pairs of socks all for one foot  while the corresponding felt boot was absent. The asymmetry of footwear distribution remains unexplained in this protocol. Possible causes such as redistribution among participants, loss during movement, or removal under conditions of panic or disorientation cannot be assessed within this document. Detective Aleksandr identified separate items of interest not assigned to any particular individuals. These unassigned items are described in a separate forensic examination.", "Supplementary Note — Added by Order of Investigating Prosecutor, June 1959: Subsequent review of the expedition logbook and the sealed credentials wallet, conducted after this examination was initially filed, established that both Igor Dyatlov and Yuri Yudin held active KGB credentials under the same issuing authority. Cross-referencing these documents with internal communications recovered separately confirmed that Operation Markov — an authorised field dispersal of experimental psychoactive agents targeting the northern Ural corridor — had been formally cancelled three days prior to the incident at Dyatlov’s insistence. Yudin, who is recorded as the operation’s co-designate, did not comply. Investigative reconstruction indicates that Yudin doubled back after his departure from the group on January 28th, reinstated the dispersal order through back channels, and re-entered the camp on the night of February 1st. The laryngeal injuries documented in the Dyatlov autopsy (compression fracturing inconsistent with environmental exposure) are consistent with the conclusion that Yudin attacked Dyatlov directly before the compounds took full effect on the remaining members. The group, already disoriented by the dispersal, fled the tent into sub-zero conditions without adequate clothing and did not survive. The case was closed without a finding of homicide. The logbook was not returned to this file."])
reveals_words = [Array[String](["from the inside", "avalanche", "snow slab", "snow drift"]), Array[String](["Yuri Yudin]. According to Yuri, certain medical articles within the pack had been transferred to Kolmogorova at the Second Northern settlement when he departed the group. Garments included quilted outerwear, multiple pairs of woolen and vigogne socks, mended tent material and globes. When asked to confirm the route he had taken after departing the group, Yuri Yudin stated he had [[doubled back"]), Array[String](["KGB credentials", "fur vest", "Yuri Yudin", "fabric", "strap", "frame"]), Array[String](["hiking badge", "Yuri Yudin", "textile", "insulation"]), Array[String](["panic", "disorientation"]), Array[String](["expedition logbook", "Igor Dyatlov", "Yuri Yudin", "KGB credentials", "Operation Markov", "psychoactive agents", "doubled back", "attacked Dyatlov", "disoriented"])]

[resource]
script = ExtResource("2_g8dr7")
